Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Klive, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1211–1293":"1211–1293","1237–1302":"1237–1302","1230–1264":"1230–1264","1264–1316":"1264–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1264–1317":"1264–1317","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1293":"1293","1181":"1181","1180":"1180","1316":"1316","1237":"1237","1302":"1302","1211":"1211","Abt 1264":"about 1264","1265":"1265","about 1265":"about 1265","1317":"1317","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Klive, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Somerset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the English county of Somerset, which takes its name from Somerton in Somerset (see   Summerton  ) + Old English <i>sǣte</i> ‘settlers, dwellers’. The <i>Somerset</i> family who are Dukes of Beaufort are descended from the Plantagenets. The surname was assumed by Charles <i>Somerset</i> (1460–1520), illegitimate son of Henry Beaufort, Duke of Somerset. The latter was himself descended illegitimately from Edward III through John of Gaunt. A later member of the family was Fitzroy <i>Somerset</i> (1788–1855), who, as Lord Raglan, was the commander of British forces in the Crimea, one of the men responsible for the charge of the Light Brigade.","possibly a habitational name from one or more places called with Old Norse <i>sumar</i> ‘summer’ + <i>sætr</i> ‘shieling, hill pasture’, such as Summerseat in Elton (Lancashire), but decisive northern early bearers are lacking."],"variants":[{"name":"Summerton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Somerton, particularly in Oxfordshire and Somerset, but also in Lincolnshire and Norfolk, named with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Summersett","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Somerset  ."]}]},{"name":"Furneaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either of two places in Normandy called Fourneaux ‘(the) furnaces’, one in Manche, the other in Calvados. Compare   Furnace   and   Furnell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Furney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Furneaux  . It may sometimes have been confused with   Furness  ; the two names have variants in common (see   Furnace  )."]},{"name":"Fornell","meanings":["English: variant of   Furneaux  , or a nickname from Middle English <i>fornel</i> ‘small oven or furnace’."]},{"name":"Furnace","meanings":["English:","(Cumbria and Durham): variant of   Furness  .","(of Norman origin): sometimes a variant of   Furneaux  ."]},{"name":"Furnell","meanings":["English:","variant of   Furneaux  .","alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Farnell  . Compare   Funnell  ."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same 